To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I hereby request copies of all records in the possession of USAID related to: (1) the procurement and delivery of energy infrastructure equipment to Ukraine in connection with the Russia-Ukraine war; (2) specifically, USAID's acquisition and transfer of a GE TM2500 aeroderivative gas turbine to Ukraine in or around early 2023; and (3) any internal assessments of corruption risks in the delivery of energy aid to Ukraine.

PART I — PROCUREMENT AND DELIVERY OF ENERGY INFRASTRUCTURE AID

I request all records from February 1, 2022 through December 31, 2024, including but not limited to:

Program documents, project plans, statements of work, and implementation frameworks governing USAID's energy infrastructure assistance to Ukraine, including but not limited to the procurement and delivery of transformers, mobile boiler houses, mobile heating units, grid repair equipment, and power generation assets;
Procurement records related to the above, including solicitations, contracts, task orders, purchase orders, and modifications, and the names of all prime contractors and significant subcontractors involved in energy equipment procurement for Ukraine;
Records relating to the selection, prioritization, and targeting criteria used to determine which energy infrastructure assets to procure and where to direct them within Ukraine;
Communications between USAID and the U.S. Department of State, Department of Energy, Department of Defense, or National Security Council regarding the scope, prioritization, or implementation of energy infrastructure aid to Ukraine;
Any after-action reports, monitoring and evaluation records, or program performance assessments related to energy infrastructure assistance to Ukraine.

PART II — GE TM2500 GAS TURBINE PROCUREMENT AND TRANSFER

In approximately February 2023, USAID purchased a GE TM2500 aeroderivative gas turbine generator, which was subsequently shipped to Ukraine from Arizona on a Ukrainian Antonov cargo aircraft. I request all records related to this transaction and transfer, including:

The procurement record, contract, or purchase order for the TM2500 unit, including the contracting vehicle used, the price paid, and the identity of all parties to the transaction;
Any sole-source justification or competitive acquisition documentation associated with the purchase;
Communications between USAID officials and GE Gas Power / GE Vernova — including representatives such as Aman Joshi (General Manager, Aeroderivatives) or other GE personnel — regarding the turbine's procurement, delivery logistics, installation, or commissioning;
Records reflecting how the specific need for a TM2500 was identified and approved within USAID, including any approvals from the Office of the Administrator or relevant mission directors;
Logistics, shipping, and transfer documentation covering the movement of the turbine from the United States to Ukraine;
Records related to the installation and commissioning of the turbine within Ukraine, including communications with Ukrenergo or other Ukrainian counterparts and any third-party contractors involved on the ground;
Any follow-up reporting on the turbine's operational status, performance, or condition after delivery.

PART III — CORRUPTION RISK ASSESSMENTS IN ENERGY AID DELIVERY

I request all records reflecting any internal or commissioned assessments, analyses, audits, or reviews of corruption risks, diversion risks, or accountability gaps in the delivery of energy infrastructure assistance to Ukraine, including:

Any risk assessments or due diligence reviews conducted prior to or during the design of energy aid programs in Ukraine, addressing the potential for procurement fraud, equipment diversion, or misappropriation;
Internal guidance, policies, or escalation procedures developed specifically for the Ukraine energy aid context in response to identified corruption risks;
Communications between USAID's Office of Inspector General and program offices regarding oversight of energy infrastructure procurements or deliveries to Ukraine;
Any third-party assessments, contractor deliverables, or reports commissioned by USAID that address governance, accountability, or anti-corruption measures in the Ukrainian energy sector aid pipeline;
Records of any specific incidents, flags, or referrals related to potential misuse or diversion of energy equipment aid to Ukraine, to the extent not classified.

KEY OFFICIALS

Relevant officials likely include: USAID Administrator Samantha Power (2021-2023), the Director of USAID's Ukraine Mission, and officials in the Bureau for Europe and Eurasia and the Office of Acquisition and Assistance. I ask that records custodians search email accounts, shared drives, and contract management systems associated with these officials and offices for the requested period.

FEE WAIVER REQUEST

I request a waiver of all fees pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(4)(A)(iii). I am a journalist engaged in research for a book on U.S. energy policy and the geopolitical dimensions of the Russia-Ukraine war. The requested records concern how U.S. taxpayer funds were used to procure and deliver energy infrastructure to Ukraine, and whether adequate safeguards existed to prevent diversion or misuse. Disclosure is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to public understanding of federal foreign assistance activity. This request is not made for commercial purposes. If a full waiver is not granted, I request that fees be limited to duplication costs only, and that I be notified before any fees exceeding $25.00 are incurred.

EXPEDITED PROCESSING REQUEST

I request expedited processing pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(E) on the grounds of urgency to inform the public concerning actual or alleged federal government activity. Questions about the accountability of U.S. energy aid to Ukraine are of ongoing and significant public concern, including in the context of Congressional oversight of foreign assistance programs.

FORM OF PRODUCTION

Please produce all responsive records in electronic format (PDF or searchable text) via email or electronic delivery. If any records are withheld in whole or in part, I request a Vaughn index identifying each withheld record, the exemption(s) claimed, and a particularized explanation. I also request that all reasonably segregable, non-exempt portions of withheld records be released.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tim McDonnell

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I hereby request copies of all records in the possession of the Department of the Treasury — including the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC), the Office of Terrorism and Financial Intelligence (TFI), the Office of International Affairs, and the Office of Economic Policy — related to: (1) the design and calibration of the Russian oil price cap mechanism, including deliberations over the $60/barrel ceiling; (2) communications with G7 partners on the design of energy sanctions against Russia, including decisions about what to exclude from sanctions; and (3) any unclassified analysis of how Ukrainian long-range drone and missile strikes on Russian oil refining infrastructure could affect Russian export revenues and the price cap mechanism.

The requested time period is February 1, 2022 through December 31, 2025.

PART I — CALIBRATION OF THE $60/BARREL PRICE CAP: INTERNAL DELIBERATIONS

I request all records related to the internal Treasury deliberations over the design and specific calibration of the Russian oil price cap, including:

Internal memoranda, options papers, analytical reports, or briefing materials assessing what price level the cap should be set at, including analysis of why $60 per barrel was selected over alternative levels and what economic or geopolitical criteria were used to determine that figure;
Records reflecting Treasury's analysis of the tradeoff between maximizing Russian revenue loss and maintaining global oil market stability, including any modeling of oil price impacts under different cap level scenarios;
Internal communications — including those involving Under Secretary for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence Brian E. Nelson, Deputy Secretary Wally Adeyemo, and Secretary Janet Yellen — related to the design and calibration of the price cap between February 2022 and December 2022;
Records reflecting any deliberations over whether or when to revise or tighten the $60/barrel cap following its implementation, including any analyses of the cap's effectiveness in reducing Russian revenues, assessments of the 'shadow fleet' circumventing the cap, and any options papers prepared on lowering or restructuring the cap level;
Any Treasury analyses of the cap's effectiveness over time, including internal assessments of the degree to which Russian Urals crude was trading above or below the cap, and the fiscal impact on the Russian federal budget;
Records related to discussions of whether ESPO (Eastern Siberia-Pacific Ocean) crude and other Russian grades exported via Pacific ports should be subject to a separate or differently calibrated cap.

PART II — G7 COMMUNICATIONS ON ENERGY SANCTIONS DESIGN AND EXCLUSIONS

I request all records related to Treasury's communications and negotiations with G7 partners — including finance ministries, foreign ministries, and relevant EU institutions — on the design of energy sanctions against Russia, with particular attention to decisions about what to exclude from sanctions coverage:

Records of communications between Treasury officials and counterparts in Germany, France, Italy, the European Commission, or other G7/EU partners regarding the exclusion of Russian pipeline natural gas from sanctions coverage, including the reasoning behind that exclusion and any internal U.S. assessments of its implications;
Records reflecting Treasury's analysis of — or communications with European partners about — the continued flow of Russian gas through pipelines to EU member states (including Hungary, Austria, Slovakia, and others) during the period of the request, and any U.S. assessments of the diplomatic or economic consequences of sanctioning pipeline gas;
Records related to OFAC licensing decisions that carved out specific energy transactions or counterparties from Russia sanctions coverage, including any deliberations over which Russian state energy entities (e.g., Gazprom, Rosneft, Transneft, Lukoil) to sanction, when, and with what carve-outs;
Communications between Treasury and G7 partners regarding the scope of services covered by the maritime services ban underlying the price cap, including any discussions of gaps or loopholes identified in the coalition's coverage;
Any Treasury assessments of the use by Russia of non-coalition intermediaries — including in the UAE, Turkey, India, or China — to circumvent the price cap or energy sanctions, and any related diplomatic communications with those countries;
Records of G7 finance ministers' meetings or working group sessions where energy sanctions design, exclusions, or the price cap mechanism were substantively discussed, including any U.S. preparatory materials or readouts from those sessions.

PART III — ANALYSIS OF UKRAINIAN STRIKES ON RUSSIAN OIL REFINING CAPACITY

Beginning in 2024, Ukraine conducted a series of long-range drone and missile strikes against Russian oil refineries and fuel depots, including facilities operated by Rosneft, Lukoil, and other Russian energy companies. I request all unclassified records in which Treasury analyzed the implications of these strikes for Russian oil export revenues, the price cap mechanism, or global energy markets, including:

Any unclassified Treasury or OFAC analyses assessing the impact of Ukrainian strikes on Russian refining capacity on Russia's ability to generate oil export revenues, and the interaction between reduced refining capacity and the price cap mechanism;
Records reflecting internal Treasury deliberations over whether Ukrainian strikes on Russian energy infrastructure were consistent with, or posed risks to, the goals of the price cap policy — including any tension between degrading Russian energy revenue on one hand and risking global market disruption on the other;
Communications between Treasury officials and counterparts at the State Department, NSC, or NEC regarding the Ukrainian drone strike campaign against Russian refineries and its implications for U.S. energy sanctions policy;
Any Treasury assessments of the impact of refinery strikes on the global refined products market, including diesel and gasoline price effects, and whether such strikes affected the price cap's effectiveness or required any policy adjustments;
Records reflecting communications between Treasury and G7 partners on the refinery strike campaign and its implications for coalition energy sanctions policy or the price cap mechanism.

To the extent any records responsive to Part III are classified, I request that Treasury identify those records in its Vaughn index and produce any reasonably segregable unclassified portions. I note that the economic and market impact dimensions of the refinery strikes — as distinct from operational or intelligence dimensions — are likely to be substantially unclassified and should be produced in full.

KEY OFFICIALS

Relevant officials for the requested period include: Secretary Janet Yellen and Secretary Scott Bessent, Deputy Secretary Wally Adeyemo, the Under Secretary for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence, OFAC Director, the Assistant Secretary for International Finance, and the Assistant Secretary for Economic Policy. I ask that records custodians search email accounts, shared drives, and relevant policy and legal workspaces associated with these officials and the OFAC, TFI, and Office of International Affairs for the full requested period.

NOTE ON DELIBERATIVE PROCESS PRIVILEGE

Treasury may seek to withhold portions of responsive records under Exemption 5's deliberative process privilege. I ask that Treasury apply this privilege narrowly and in conformity with the presidential memorandum of March 19, 2009, directing agencies to apply FOIA exemptions only where disclosure would cause foreseeable harm. Final analyses, completed studies, and post-decisional records — including any assessments produced after the cap was set at $60/barrel or after specific OFAC determinations were issued — are not shielded by the deliberative process privilege and should be produced in full. Where pre-decisional records are withheld, I request that factual portions be segregated and produced.

FEE WAIVER REQUEST

I request a waiver of all fees pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(4)(A)(iii). I am a journalist engaged in research for a book on U.S. energy policy and the geopolitical dimensions of the Russia-Ukraine war. The price cap mechanism is one of the most consequential instruments of economic statecraft deployed in the conflict, and the deliberations surrounding its calibration and design are of substantial and direct public interest. Disclosure will contribute significantly to public understanding of how the U.S. government crafted and implemented this policy. This request is not made for commercial purposes. If a full waiver is not granted, I request that fees be limited to duplication costs only, and that I be notified before any fees exceeding $25.00 are incurred.

EXPEDITED PROCESSING REQUEST

I request expedited processing pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(E). The Russian oil price cap and associated energy sanctions remain active policy instruments with significant ongoing consequences for the war in Ukraine, global energy markets, and U.S. foreign policy. Timely disclosure will contribute directly to informed public debate about the effectiveness and design of these measures.

FORM OF PRODUCTION

Please produce all responsive records in electronic format (PDF or searchable text) via email or electronic delivery. If any records are withheld in whole or in part, I request a Vaughn index identifying each withheld record, the exemption(s) claimed, and a particularized explanation of how the exemption applies. I also request that all reasonably segregable, non-exempt portions of withheld records be released.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tim McDonnell

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I hereby request copies of all records related to the Department of Energy's contingency planning, economic analysis, and operational response regarding potential or actual disruptions to oil and natural gas transit through the Strait of Hormuz, including records produced both before and after the closure of the Strait by Iranian forces beginning in March 2026.

PART I — PRE-CONFLICT CONTINGENCY PLANNING (January 1, 2024 – February 27, 2026)
I request all records within this period related to:

Internal analyses, scenario-planning documents, or contingency plans prepared by DOE, the Energy Information Administration (EIA), or the Office of Fossil Energy and Carbon Management (FECM) assessing the potential economic and market impacts of a full or partial closure of the Strait of Hormuz;
Any modeling or quantitative analysis of the impact of a Hormuz closure on U.S. domestic gasoline prices, natural gas prices, or broader inflation indicators;
Records related to the adequacy and planned drawdown strategy for the Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) in the event of a major Gulf supply disruption, including any updates to SPR emergency drawdown protocols specifically contemplating a Hormuz closure scenario;
Communications between DOE and the International Energy Agency (IEA) regarding coordinated strategic reserve release protocols in a Hormuz disruption scenario;
Communications between DOE and the National Security Council, National Economic Council, or White House regarding energy market contingency planning related to Iran or the Strait of Hormuz;
Any EIA special reports, briefing documents, or internal analyses prepared for senior DOE or White House officials assessing Hormuz closure risks.

PART II — CRISIS RESPONSE (February 28, 2026 – Present)
I request all records from the onset of U.S.-Israeli military operations against Iran through the date of this request related to:

All records relating to the decision to authorize and execute SPR drawdowns in response to the Strait of Hormuz closure, including internal deliberations on drawdown volumes, timing, and coordination with IEA member states;
EIA analyses and market impact assessments produced after the closure of the Strait, including any assessments of SPR adequacy relative to the projected duration of the closure;
Communications between DOE and the IEA regarding coordinated emergency oil reserve releases in response to the Hormuz closure;
Records reflecting DOE's assessment of alternative supply routes or sources, including Saudi Arabia's East-West Pipeline, UAE's Abu Dhabi Crude Oil Pipeline (ADCOP), and potential increases in U.S. domestic production or LNG exports;
Any briefings or communications prepared for the Secretary of Energy, Deputy Secretary, or the White House regarding the trajectory of oil and gas prices and the adequacy of existing response tools;
Records related to coordination with major oil-importing allies — including Japan, South Korea, India, and EU member states — regarding burden-sharing in emergency reserve releases.

KEY OFFICIALS

Relevant officials include: Secretary of Energy Chris Wright, Deputy Secretary, the Administrator of the EIA, and senior officials in the Office of Fossil Energy and Carbon Management. I ask that records custodians search email accounts, shared drives, and relevant crisis management systems for these officials for the requested period.

FEE WAIVER REQUEST

I request a waiver of all fees pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(4)(A)(iii). I am a journalist engaged in research for a book on U.S. energy policy and the geopolitical dimensions of the Iran conflict. Disclosure of the requested records will contribute significantly to public understanding of how the U.S. government planned for and responded to one of the most consequential energy supply disruptions in recent history. This request is not made for commercial purposes. If a full waiver is not granted, I request that fees be limited to duplication costs only, and that I be notified before any fees exceeding $25.00 are incurred.

EXPEDITED PROCESSING REQUEST

I request expedited processing pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(E). The closure of the Strait of Hormuz is an ongoing crisis with immediate and severe consequences for U.S. energy markets, inflation, and foreign policy. Timely disclosure of the requested records will contribute directly to urgent public debate about how the U.S. government prepared for and is managing this crisis.

FORM OF PRODUCTION

Please produce all responsive records in electronic format (PDF or searchable text) via email or electronic delivery. If any records are withheld in whole or in part, I request a Vaughn index identifying each withheld record, the exemption(s) claimed, and a particularized explanation of how the exemption applies. I also request that all reasonably segregable, non-exempt portions of withheld records be released.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tim McDonnell
